children.label: captive
children.definition: Individuals in captivity or quarantine (i.e. individuals provided with conditions suitable for them, but explicit measures of containment are in place)

children.label: casual
children.definition: Individuals surviving outside of captivity or cultivation in a location, no reproduction

children.label: colonising
children.definition: Self-sustaining population outside of captivity or cultivation, with individuals surviving a significant distance from the original point of introduction

children.label: cultivated
children.definition: Individuals in cultivation (i.e. individuals provided with conditions suitable for them, but explicit measures to prevent dispersal are limited at best)

children.label: established
children.definition: Individuals surviving outside of captivity or cultivation in a location, reproduction occurring, and population self-sustaining

children.label: failing
children.definition: Individuals released outside of captivity or cultivation in a location, but incapable of surviving for a significant period

children.label: invasive
children.definition: Self-sustaining population outside of captivity or cultivation, with individuals surviving and reproducing a significant distance from the original point of introduction

children.label: managed
children.definition: Under direct control and maintenance of humans

children.label: native
children.definition: Not transported beyond limits of native range

children.label: naturalized
children.definition: Able to persist at the point of introduction either sexually or asexually, but not spreading

children.label: released
children.definition: Individuals directly released into novel environment

children.label: reproducing
children.definition: Individuals surviving outside of captivity or cultivation in a location, reproduction is occurring, but population not self-sustaining

children.label: spreading
children.definition: Dispersing from the point of introduction into new areas

children.label: unestablished
children.definition: Occurring impermanently or transitorily

children.label: widespreadInvasive
children.definition: Fully invasive species, with individuals dispersing, surviving and reproducing at multiple sites across a greater or lesser spectrum of habitats and extent of occurrence

children.label: Adult
children.definition: An adult is an organism that has reached sexual maturity

children.label: Calyptopsis
children.definition: Calyptopsis In Euphausiacea, one of the larval stage is called calyptopsis. It is similar to zoea larva in all respects except that the paired eyes are sessile i.e. not stalked

children.label: Caterpillar
children.definition: Caterpillars are the larval stage of members of the order Lepidoptera (the insect order comprising butterflies and moths)

children.label: Chick
children.definition: A chick is a bird that has not yet reached adulthood

children.label: Cyprid
children.definition: The cyprid larva is the last larval stage before adulthood

children.label: Cyst
children.definition: A cyst is a closed sac, having a distinct envelop and division compared with the nearby tissue

children.label: Deutonymph
children.definition: A second larval form occurring in the development of most mites

children.label: Eft
children.definition: The juvenile stage of a newt

children.label: Egg
children.definition: The egg is the organic vessel containing the zygote in which an embryo develops until it can survive on its own, at which point the animal hatches

children.label: Embryo
children.definition: An embryo refers to the early developmental stage of eukaryotic organisms following the fertilization of an egg (derived from a female) by sperm (derived from a male) as a method of sexual reproduction

children.label: Fetus
children.definition: A fetus is the unborn offspring of an animal that develops from an embryo

children.label: Fledgling
children.definition: A fledgling is a young bird that has recently become capable of flight, but is still dependent upon parental care and feeding.

children.label: Flowering
children.definition: The flowering stage refers to the phase where plants produce their flower sets, vegetables, and fruits

children.label: Fruiting
children.definition: The process of a tree or other plant producing fruit

children.label: Furcilia
children.definition: An intermediate larva of a euphausid in which eye development is nearly adult but biramous swimming appendages are retained

children.label: Gametophyte
children.definition: A gametophyte is one of the two alternating phases in the life cycle of plants and algae

children.label: Hatchling
children.definition: A hatchling is a young bird that has recently come out of its egg

children.label: Imago
children.definition: The imago is the last stage an insect attains during its metamorphosis, its process of growth and development

children.label: Immature
children.definition: Not fully developed

children.label: Juvenile
children.definition: A juvenile is an individual organism that has not yet reached its adult form, sexual maturity or size

children.label: Larva
children.definition: A larva is a distinct juvenile form many animals undergo before metamorphosis into adults

children.label: Mature
children.definition: Fully developed physically

children.label: Medusa
children.definition: A medusa is a form of cnidarian in which the body is shaped like an umbrella

children.label: Megalopa
children.definition: The final larval stage found in decapod crustaceans

children.label: Metanauplius
children.definition: Metanauplius is an early larval stage of some crustaceans such as krill. It follows the nauplius stage

children.label: Nauplius
children.definition: The first larval stage of many crustaceans, having an unsegmented body and a single eye.

children.label: Neonate
children.definition: A neonate is a newborn mammal

children.label: Nestling
children.definition: A nestling is a bird that is too young to leave its nest

children.label: Nymph
children.definition: A nymph is the immature form of some invertebrates, particularly insects, which undergoes gradual metamorphosis (hemimetabolism) before reaching its adult stage

children.label: Polyp
children.definition: A solitary or colonial sedentary form of a coelenterate such as a sea anemone, typically having a columnar body with the mouth uppermost surrounded by a ring of tentacles. In some species, polyps are a phase in the life cycle which alternates with a medusoid phase.

children.label: Pupa
children.definition: A pupa is the life stage of some insects undergoing transformation between immature and mature stages

children.label: Seedling
children.definition: A seedling is a young plant sporophyte developing out of a plant embryo from a seed

children.label: Subadult
children.definition: A subadult is an organism that is not fully adult

children.label: Tadpole
children.definition: The tailed aquatic larva of an amphibian (frog, toad, newt, or salamander), breathing through gills and lacking legs until the later stages of its development.

children.label: Unknown
children.definition: Unknown life stage

children.label: Vegetative
children.definition: Relating to or denoting reproduction or propagation achieved by asexual means, either naturally (budding, rhizomes, runners, bulbs, etc.) or artificially (grafting, layering, or taking cuttings)

children.label: Veliger
children.definition: The final larval stage of certain molluscs, having two ciliated flaps for swimming and feeding

children.label: Zoea
children.definition: A free-swimming planktonic larval form of many decapod crustaceans and especially crabs that has a relatively large cephalothorax, conspicuous eyes, and fringed antennae and mouthparts

children.label: Zygote
children.definition: A zygote is a eukaryotic cell formed by a fertilization event between two gametes

children.label: agriculture
children.definition: Plants grown with then intention of harvesting.

children.label: aquacultureMariculture
children.definition: The analog of agriculture and farmed animals, specifically related to aquatic organisms.

children.label: ballastWater
children.definition: Organisms transported within the water pumped into boats and ships to provide ballast.

children.label: biologicalControl
children.definition: Organisms occuring in an area because they were introduced for the purpose of biological control of another organism.

children.label: conservationOrWildlifeManagement
children.definition: Organisms introduced for conservation purposes or wildlife management.

children.label: containerBulk
children.definition: Stowaways transported in or on the cargo containers or bulk cargo units themselves.

children.label: contaminantNursery
children.definition: Organisms transported into an area together with plant material.

children.label: contaminantOnAnimals
children.definition: Contaminants carried either on or in the body of transported animals.

children.label: contaminantOnPlants
children.definition: Organisms transported on plant material.

children.label: contaminateBait
children.definition: Contaminants, pathogens and parasites transported with live, frozen or preserved bait used to catch fish or other organisms.

children.label: corridor
children.definition: Infrastructure, such as bridges, tunnels and canals have removed natural barriers to dispersal and allowed a species to move into a novel location.

children.label: corridorAndDispersal
children.definition: Organisms dispersed naturally, even if that dispersal was aided by changes in the landscape created by humans.

children.label: erosionControl
children.definition: Organisms introduced for the purpose of erosion control/dune stabilization (windbreaks, hedges, etc).

children.label: escapeFromConfinement
children.definition: Organisms intentionally transported by humans and intended to be kept in captivity or cultivation, but having inadvertently escaped from human control.

children.label: farmedAnimals
children.definition: Animals cared for and bred with the specific intention of using their products, such as meat and milk.

children.label: fisheryInTheWild
children.definition: Fish stocked into the wild either to create a fishery or for recreational angling.

children.label: fishingEquipment
children.definition: Aquatic organisms moved between sites on equipment of recreational anglers and professional fishermen.

children.label: foodContaminant
children.definition: Foods for human consumption, whether they are transported life or dead.

children.label: forestry
children.definition: Trees specifically introduced to provide timber and other forestry products.

children.label: fur
children.definition: Organisms escaped from a fur farms, including unauthorised releases.

children.label: hitchhikersAirplane
children.definition: Organisms that enter airplanes or other aircraft, such as helicopters, and are transported by them to another location.

children.label: hitchhikersShip
children.definition: Organisms that enter directly onto boats or ships and are transported by them to another location.

children.label: horticulture
children.definition: Plants distributed by the ornamental and decorative plants industry.

children.label: hullFouling
children.definition: Organisms that attach themselves to the subsurface hull of boats and ships.

children.label: hunting
children.definition: Animals stocked into the wild specifically with the intention that they would be hunted for sport.

children.label: intentional
children.definition: Organisms were brought to new area with the specific intention of keeping them alive in the new region, regardless of whether they were intended to be cultivated or released into the wild.

children.label: landscapeImprovement
children.definition: Landscape/flora/fauna "improvement" in the wild.

children.label: liveFoodLiveBait
children.definition: Live food imported for human consumption, such as shellfish and snails, and for live bait.

children.label: machineryEquipment
children.definition: Organisms carried on the surfaces of or within heavy machinery and equipment.

children.label: naturalDispersal
children.definition: Dispersal of organisms to new regions by natural dispersal from regions in which they are alien.

children.label: ornamentalNonHorticulture
children.definition: Ornamental plants introduced through pathways other than the horticultural industry.

children.label: otherEscape
children.definition: Organisms brought into an area with the intention of keeping them in captivity permanently, but that have subsequently escaped.

children.label: otherIntentionalRelease
children.definition: A catch-all for intentional releases not for human use that are not covered by other more specific terms.

children.label: otherTransport
children.definition: A catchall term for any transport related dispersal that is not covered in other terms.

children.label: packingMaterial
children.definition: Organic material, particularly unprocessed plant material that is used to pack transported goods.

children.label: parasitesOnAnimals
children.definition: Parasitic and pathogenic organisms transported with their host or vector animal.

children.label: parasitesOnPlants
children.definition: Parasitic and pathogenic organisms transported with their host or vector plant.

children.label: people
children.definition: Organisms transported on people themselves and/or their personal luggage.

children.label: pet
children.definition: Privately kept animals.

children.label: publicGardenZooAquaria
children.definition: Organisms in public collections of plants and/or animals.

children.label: releasedForUse
children.definition: Release in nature for use (other than above, e.g., fur, transport, medical use).

children.label: releaseInNature
children.definition: Organisms transported and released by humans in a (semi)natural environment with the intention that they should live their without further human aid.

children.label: research
children.definition: Plants and animals introduced for the purpose of breeding, scientific and medical research, including science education.

children.label: seedContaminant
children.definition: Organisms contaminating transported seeds.

children.label: timberTrade
children.definition: Contaminants on unprocessed timber, processed wood and wood derived products.

children.label: transportationHabitatMaterial
children.definition: Organisms transported with their habitat material to a new location.

children.label: transportContaminant
children.definition: An umbrella term for all species transported as contaninents in other products.

children.label: transportStowaway
children.definition: An umbrella term for all species transported by riding on forms of transport where the organism has a direct interation with the transport and is not merely carried as part of, or a contaminent of cargo.

children.label: tunnelsBridges
children.definition: Unintentional dispersal by organisms using artificial tunnels, bridges, roads and railways.

children.label: unaided
children.definition: Organisms that spread by natural dispersal, without action or assistance by humans, from regions in which they are also alien.

children.label: unintentional
children.definition: The organism was unintentionally brought to a new region.

children.label: vehicles
children.definition: Other vehicle hitchhikers that have been unintentionally dispersed, but are not covered by other terms.

children.label: waterwaysBasinsSeas
children.definition: Organisms that dispersed through artificial waterways created to connect previosuly unconnected water bodies.
